"# Appendix G — Where To Go Next

You finished the book. What now?

## Read a program you didn't write

The single fastest way to level up. Look at somebody else's Motoi Scheme code and *read it, top to bottom*. Try to understand what every line does. When you hit something you don't recognize, `,help` it.

Places to find real Motoi code:

- **`scheme-books/`** in your Motoi installation. There are companion books for music, motion, animation, arcade games, and more — each has runnable examples.
- **`carts/`** if it exists in your install — small self-contained programs you can eval.
- **The reference** — even that has an `:example` per verb, and reading them is a mini-tour of the language.

## Build the thing that scared you

Everyone has a project they've thought about but felt too big.

For you, right now, it's probably still too big. But it's *closer* than you think. Break it in pieces. Build the smallest visible slice.

- Want a game? Build a version where a dot moves. Then add a wall. Then add a coin. Then add a score. Then a title screen.
- Want a music tool? Build a version that plays one note. Then a scale. Then a sequenced pattern. Then a keyboard-input surface.
- Want a physics simulation? Build a version with one falling ball. Then bouncing off the floor. Then two balls colliding. Then Newton's cradle.

The smallest slice is always tractable. Motoi's kid-scale surface — grid, entities, audio, cortex — is enough for any of these to reach *something visible* in a hundred lines.

## Explore a module

Read the appendix (Appendix B). Pick a module that sounds interesting. Read its `MANIFEST.slat`. Pick a verb from its `reference.slat`. Try it in the REPL. Build something small using it.

Good starting modules for exploration:

- **`math-curves`** — easing functions. Immediate visual/audible payoff.
- **`game-ai-advanced`** — steering behaviors. Enemies that chase, wander, flee.
- **`music-advanced`** — vintage kit emulations, patterns.
- **`math-plot`** — draw a chart of any function.

## Read the SICP book

SICP — *Structure and Interpretation of Computer Programs* by Abelson & Sussman — is the classic Scheme book. It teaches deeply how programming works, using a Scheme dialect very similar to Motoi. Free online.

If you liked this book, you'll like SICP. It'll take you six months to a year to work through, and you'll be a *dramatically* better programmer at the end. Reading it cover-to-cover is one of the most reliable career-boosting acts in software.

Note: SICP uses standard Scheme (MIT Scheme, or Racket), not Motoi. Nearly everything transfers — the syntax is the same, the semantics almost the same. When you meet something SICP does that Motoi doesn't (or vice versa), that's a small research task and it teaches you both languages better.

## Read the companion books

Motoi ships with a family of specialty books, each ~10-100 pages, going deep on one area.

- **Book of Music** — theory, notation, chord progressions, ear training.
- **Book of Motion** — animation curves, keyframing, feel.
- **Book of Animation** — cartoon principles applied to code.
- **Book of Instruments** — building your own synths.
- **Book of Systems** — process, scheduling, IPC.
- **Book of SLAT** — the SLAT file format Motoi uses for everything.
- **Book of CS Curriculum** — the general shape of computer science.
- **Book of Arcade Games** — recreating retro games.
- **Book of Simulation Games** — Conway's Life, ecosystem models.
- **Book of Logic** — propositional and predicate logic in Scheme.
- **Book of Math** — algebra, geometry, discrete math.
- **Book of Motoi (Jesse)** — a specific fictional character's whole coursework.

Pick the ones that pull you.

## Contribute back

If you build something using Motoi Scheme and you think other people would enjoy it — share it.

- Post to a forum, a Discord, a blog.
- Contribute a code example to a companion book.
- Add a verb to your own module and publish it.
- Report bugs. Suggest improvements. Ask for features.

Motoi is a young language and grows through use. Every real program someone shares teaches the maintainers what to build next.

## Learn a second language

After Motoi, learn a language *different* from Scheme. The contrast will teach you about both.

Good second languages:

- **Racket** — a modern Scheme with a huge library. Nearly identical syntax to Motoi.
- **Clojure** — a Lisp on the Java VM. Focuses on immutability and concurrency.
- **JavaScript** — because it's everywhere. Different vibes, same functional core.
- **Python** — most readable general-purpose language. Different syntax, similar concepts.
- **Rust** — an entirely different corner of the design space. Type systems, memory safety.

Each of these will hand you a new lens on programming. The point isn't to abandon Scheme — it's to see what Scheme is *by* seeing what it isn't.

## Learn to teach

Once you understand Motoi, teach a friend.

You'll discover — as everyone does — that the act of teaching *is* learning. Explaining why parentheses go where they go forces you to hold the mental model precisely. Answering a friend's confused question forces you to see the pieces from outside your own head.

Teach a kid, teach a sibling, teach a colleague, teach an online audience. Every hour of teaching is an hour of your own understanding getting *sharper*.

## Read the Motoi source

Motoi is open source. You can read every line of the interpreter.

`src/` is where the core lives:
- `reader.js` — parses text into S-expressions.
- `interp.js` — walks the tree and evaluates.
- `macro.js` — expands macros.
- `base.js` — installs the primitive verbs.
- `slat.js` — reads and writes SLAT files.

Reading these teaches you *how the language actually works* — every abstract concept you've learned (closures, tail calls, hygienic macros) has a concrete implementation there. If you've ever wondered *how does that get done*, this is where the answer lives.

## The general advice

Programming rewards *depth* and *breadth* over time.

**Depth** — pick one project and go deep. Spend six months building a game, or a musical instrument, or a physics engine. You'll learn things you couldn't have learned in a hundred small demos.

**Breadth** — sample widely. Try a web app, a CLI tool, a data pipeline, a game, a compiler. Each new domain teaches shape you'd never see in the others.

The people who ship interesting work have both. Deep understanding of a favorite thing, and broad exposure to enough other things that they know what borrowing looks like.

## The one thing

If you take one thing from this book, take this:

**Programming is composing small things into big things.** Motoi Scheme has few primitives. You've now met most of them. Everything else you'll ever build in Motoi — every game, every simulation, every tool — is these primitives combined.

The primitives are simple. The combinations aren't. That's where the joy is.

Go build.

## Where Motoi does not go

Sixteen chapters. You've learned what Motoi does. Before you close the book, spend one section on where Motoi does NOT go, because that shape matters too.

Motoi is small. Motoi is honest. Motoi has bounded reach on purpose, and every one of those bounds is a design choice, not a bug.

**Motoi does not reach the network.** He can serve a page from your computer, but he does not fetch. If you ask him what today's headline is, he cannot look. If you ask him to POST to your API, he cannot. His answer will be something like: *I don't have hands for that. Use `curl`, or use Claude, or paste the answer here and I'll help you reason about it.*

**Motoi does not reach the disk beyond his own sandbox.** He can read what you paste. He can write to his own directory. He cannot browse your Documents folder or read your `/etc/passwd`. His answer: *That's not in my house. If you paste the file, I'll help.*

**Motoi does not run shell commands.** He does not `system(cmd)`. He does not exec. He does not shell out. His answer: *That's your terminal's job. I can write the Scheme; you run the shell.*

**Motoi does not call external APIs.** No Etsy, no Shopify, no Stripe, no Twilio. He can teach the SHAPE of the request, but he does not send it. His answer: *Sakura might, or you paste the response and I'll parse it.*

**Motoi does not know the wall-clock time in Tokyo.** He knows what the runtime clock says. He does not have a timezone database. He does not phone NTP. His answer: *Best I can offer is what my clock says. If it's wrong, I'm wrong.*

**Motoi does not know what's on the news.** He doesn't read a feed. He can't look. His answer: *That's Claude's area, or a browser. I know Scheme.*

The pattern: Motoi is honest about what he does not have. He does not pretend. He does not fabricate. He offers you a redirect — a person, a tool, a language, a URL — for the thing he can't do.

### The fish-in-a-car story

Alfred's canonical metaphor for this is: asking Motoi to do a subsystem he does not have is the physical equivalent of putting a fish in a car and telling him to drive to Toledo, Ohio. The fish is a fine fish. The car is a fine car. Toledo exists. But the fish does not have hands, does not have feet, does not know what Toledo is. Even if you got the fish behind the wheel, nothing good happens next.

Motoi is the fish, when you ask him to fetch, or reach for hardware, or check the weather. He is honest that a fish is not the right creature for the job. He is not embarrassed by this. He suggests you use the tool that does have hands.

### Why this is a feature

The other name for 'a program that pretends to be able to do everything' is 'a program you can't trust.' If Motoi confidently answered the weather question when he can't check the weather, you would eventually catch him being wrong, and you would stop trusting anything he says — including the answers about Scheme, which he actually knows.

By telling you clearly what he can't do, Motoi earns your trust in what he CAN do. That's the whole trade. It's the same trade a good librarian, a good doctor, a good friend makes: *I don't know that one. Ask this person. Here's what I do know.*

### The Wittgenstein line, one more time

Wittgenstein wrote *the limits of my language are the limits of my world.* Motoi cashes that out operationally: his language does not have verbs for fetching, deploying, or reading your GPS. His world therefore does not include those things. He tells you honestly. He does not pretend.

That's it. That's the whole story of where Motoi does not go.

If you want the systematic version — every subsystem, one paragraph each — see Book of Systems Chapter 2. If you want the engineering-audience version — same shape, with more detail about the sandbox mechanics — see Book of Introspection Chapter 16.12. If you want the specific case of networking, see Book of Computing Chapter 8, section 8.9.

Whichever version you read, the shape is the same: honest capability, honest limit, meta-honesty, playful metaphor, redirect. Learn the shape. That's Motoi.")
